Rating: 4
This is delicious--and tastes very traditional. Two points, in addition to those above about reducing the sugar. 1) When soaking the matzoh in the water, just put the matzoh in a big bowl and add the water. But make sure to gently toss the matzoh periodically, or the bottom ones will disintegrate while the top ones are too dry. 2) You can use a 9x13 inch pan and it comes out perfect. Just the right height, I believe.

Rating: 1
At two o-clock in the morning I was forced to remake another apple kugel for the 2nd Passover night. When I first read this recipe's ingredients, I thought that it would make a wonderful sweet kugel. Unfortunately after I finished the product I found the following. 1. Use matzoh farfel or break down the matzoh boards into small equally sized pieces. 2. Use only 5 eggs instead of the 8 eggs. You get a nice consistency when mixing the eggs with the matzoh and apple mixture. 3. Use 1/2 cup of sugar in the recipe. You have the sweetness of the brown sugar, the orange juice and the raisins. No need for 1 1/2 cup of sugar added to this mixture. 4. It is a matter of taste but I added some crushed almonds 5. I did not add 4 tablespoon of margerine on the top of the recipe. It browned beautifully without the fat on top of the kugel. Would I do this recipe again? The answer is NO!

