First of all, thank God I read the previous reviews so that I knew to cut the sugar and butter content down. Thank you! I ended up making the following changes to the recipe: 1) I used 1/4 cup Splenda Brown sugar to coat the fresh fruit. 2) I added the zest and juice of 3 lemons to the fresh fruit. 3) I used 6 tablespoons of butter in total: 4 melted and 2 un the yop of the kugel before it went into the oven. 4) I used 3 Granny Smiths and 2 bananas, all sliced and peeled. 5) I used 1 cup of dried blueberries and 1 cup of dried nectarines hoping for more colour and flavour, and I was thrilled with the outcome. 6) I used 1/4 cup of Splenda instead of all the sugar. 7) I added 1/2 cup of sliced and toasted almonds sprinkled on top just prior to cutting and serving - for the crunch factor. The end result was that there was not a single crumb left over at last night's Seder and by 8AM today, I had already been called to share the recipe. It was 100% delicious. Thanks to all you Epicurious cooks!!

Rating: 4
I have another suggestion given to me by my mother-in-law, who is an excellent cook. When reading the recipe, she suggested separating the eggs, as she said it sounded like it could be on the heavy side. So I beat the whites until they were stiff, mixed the beaten yolks with the remaining ingredients, and folded in the beaten whites just before putting it into the oven. She also said not to peel the apples, as they would hold together better with the peeling on them. This was a huge hit at our seder, and I reheated the leftovers the next night and they were just as good.

