I made this twice for two seders this year, and it was definitely tasty but I do have one complaint--it did not hold together well for serving. I might not have soaked the matzoh long enough (although I did wait till it was quite soft), but I think the problem is more that the apples had no way to bind together. However, I had occassion to make it a third time for a Passover-style brunch buffet, and that time instead of 4 apples I used 1 diced apple and 3 ripe bananas sliced thin, with all other ingredients exactly the same as in the recipe. WHAT A DIFFERENCE. I liked the taste even better because I love bananas, and the consistency was fabulous--just like a bread pudding. In fact, one of my guests suggested I serve a whiskey sauce with it the next time! :) It was so well bound together with the banana substitution that I could present it in neat little squares stacked up on a plate, instead of in a messy pile in a casserole dish. And even more of it was eaten. But if you crave apple pie during Passover, then the original recipe is the way to go--just make sure the matzoh is well soaked.

